article.headline: Iowa 57, SE Louisiana 50
article.story: IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Tony Freeman came off the bench to score 15 points, JR Angle, Cyrus Tate and Justin Johnson had 10 each and Iowa came from behind to beat Southeastern Louisiana 57-50 on Saturday night. The Hawkeyes (7-6) were playing their first game since a 56-51 loss Dec. 14 to in-state rival Drake, and it showed. Iowa shot just 33.3 percent in the first half -- missing 11 straight shots at one point -- and turned it over nine times in the opening frame. But behind a 9-2 run to end the first half and a 12-4 run to start the second, Iowa rallied to move past .500. The game went back and forth in the second half, with the Lions (7-5) leading as late as the 3:01 mark. Freeman hit a 3 to put Iowa up two, and Tate made a tough jumper to extend the lead to four with 1:31 remaining. The Lions had a couple of chances to pull within one possession, but Freeman stripped Daryl Arnold on the baseline to end the threat. Iowa jumped back in the game with a technical foul on Lions head coach Jim Yarbrough at the 15:53 mark, with the Hawkeyes down eight. Angle converted a free throw and hit a 3 on Iowa's next trip down the floor. Johnson converted a jumper, and Jarryd Cole tied the game at 29 on a lay-up. Iowa made their first two shots of the game but went 12:48 without scoring, missing 11 straight shots as Southeastern Louisiana went on a 17-0 run. The Lions used their athleticism and a three-quarter court press to force Iowa into their long drought, but the Hawkeyes used a 9-2 spurt to close the gap to 25-18 at halftime. Kevyn Green led the Lions with 13 points.
